detail_description: Makishi Public Market, located in Naha's Makishi district, offers a glimpse into the historical Ryukyu Kingdom. This bustling marketplace in the Sakae-cho area is a central hub for fresh produce, meat, fish, and general merchandise. Visitors can immerse themselves in Okinawan everyday life by exploring the market and interacting with friendly merchants.
name: Makishi Public Market

excerpt: Sandy city beach below a highway flyover with showers, lifeguards, food outlets & basketball.
detail_description: Naminoue Beach is a sandy city beach located beneath a highway flyover in Naha, Okinawa. It's the only beach in the city and offers amenities such as showers, lifeguards, food outlets, and even a basketball court. Despite being situated in a bustling urban area with numerous tourist attractions and shopping spots nearby, it provides an opportunity to swim in the beautiful ocean.
name: Naminoue Beach

excerpt: Hilltop reconstructed castle on sprawling grounds & featuring sweeping city views.
detail_description: Shuri Castle, located on a hilltop with expansive grounds and panoramic city views, is a significant historical site in Okinawa. Once the palace of the Ryukyu Kingdom from 1429 to 1879, it boasted close trading ties with China and Melaka. Despite being nearly destroyed during the Battle of Okinawa in 1945, the castle has been reconstructed and stands as an impressive attraction surrounded by lush greenery and winding pathways to explore.
name: Shuri Castle

excerpt: Okinawan artwork & exhibits on history, nature & culture are featured at this contemporary museum.
detail_description: The Okinawa Prefectural Museum & Art Museum offers a contemporary showcase of Okinawan history, nature, and culture. The museum features exhibits detailing the region's history from ancient times to the present day, along with a diverse collection of sculptures, paintings, and video installations by local artists. Visitors can gain insight into both traditional and contemporary aspects of Okinawa through this combined experience.
name: Okinawa Prefectural Museum and Art Museum (Okimyu)

excerpt: Verdant city garden with rocky terrain & natural features such as a waterfall & a lake with koi.
detail_description: Fukushūen Garden, established in 1992 to commemorate the sister city relationship between Naha and Fuzhou, is a lush urban oasis nestled in the Kume neighborhood. This area has historically been a hub of Chinese culture and learning within the Ryukyu Kingdom. The garden's design reflects the deep influence of Chinese culture on Okinawan history and architecture.
name: Fukushūen Garden

excerpt: Established as a Shinto shrine in 1890, this sacred place offers festivals & views from the cliffs.
detail_description: Naminoue Shrine, established in 1890, is a significant Shinto shrine located in Naha, Okinawa. Originally built for the Ryukuyuan religion and dedicated to Nirai Kanai, it now overlooks the sea and offers stunning views from the cliffs. The shrine consists of a main hall, worship hall, and smaller shrines. It is situated near Memorial Park and Tsujiwakasa Ryokuchi Park.
name: Naminoue Shrine

excerpt: Boulevard lined with hotels, shops & restaurants, with street performances & food stalls on Sundays.
detail_description: Naha Kokusai Dori Shopping Street is a bustling boulevard in Okinawa, known for its vibrant atmosphere and diverse offerings. On Sundays, visitors can enjoy street performances and food stalls. The street is home to Kokusai Dori Yataimura, where unique restaurants serve up dishes using local Okinawan ingredients. During the day, it's a relaxing spot for lunch, while at night it transforms into a lively hub with food stalls open past midnight.
name: Naha Kokusai Dori Shopping Street

excerpt: Tranquil cobblestone street lined with traditional earthenware workshops, cafes & a pottery museum.
detail_description: Tsuboya Yachimun Street, also known as Tsuboya Yachimun Dori, is a serene cobblestone street adorned with traditional earthenware workshops, charming cafes, and a pottery museum. The street is home to unique workshops that have been crafting traditional Ryukyu-era pottery for generations. Visitors can enjoy leisurely strolls and window shopping while admiring the vibrant and skillfully crafted potteries on display.
name: Tsuboya Yachimun Street

excerpt: Tombs of the Second Shō Dynasty, housing the remains of kings, queens & their children.
detail_description: Tamaudun, a mausoleum located near Shuri Castle in Okinawa, is the resting place of the Second Shō Dynasty's royalty. Constructed in the early 16th century, it suffered damage during World War II but has since been restored and recognized as a UNESCO World Heritage Site. The mausoleum consists of two main rooms - one for kings and queens and another for princes and princesses.
name: Tamaudun

excerpt: Naha is the capital of Okinawa Prefecture, the tropical island group south of mainland Japan. It's known for Shuri Castle, the restored royal palace of the Ryukyu Kingdom, which flourished from the 1400s–1800s and invented the martial art karate. Tsuboya district is assocated with traditional ceramics like shiisa (lion-dog figures). Lined with shops, bars and restaurants, Kokusaidori is Naha's main street.
detail_description: Naha, the capital of Okinawa Prefecture, is a vibrant city with a rich cultural heritage. It's famous for Shuri Castle, the restored royal palace of the Ryukyu Kingdom, and Tsuboya district known for traditional ceramics. Kokusaidori is Naha's main street lined with shops, bars, and restaurants. The city offers diverse accommodation facilities, dining options, souvenir shops, and commercial complexes.
name: Naha

excerpt: Historic Ryukyu-dynasty property with traditional palace buildings, walking paths & a tranquil pond.
detail_description: Shikina-en Royal Gardens, a UNESCO World Heritage site, served as the secondary residence for the royal family of the Ryukyu Kingdom. This historic property features traditional palace buildings, walking paths, and a serene pond at its center. The garden's design includes a large pond shaped like the Chinese character for heart and an elegant gazebo on a small island in the middle of the pond.
name: Shikina-en Royal Gardens 識名園

excerpt: Kokusai is a lively downtown retail and entertainment hub with Western and Okinawan boutiques on main thoroughfare Kokusai Dori. Adjoining Tsuboya has a cluster of ceramics workshops around a pottery museum. Young crowds hit rock bars, nightclubs, and champuru stir-fry restaurants on lively side streets, and specialist vendors serve sushi at Makashi market. Midorigaoka Park is a welcome green space amid the neon.
detail_description: Kokusai Dori is a bustling downtown area in Okinawa, featuring a mix of Western and Okinawan boutiques along its main thoroughfare. The adjacent Tsuboya area is known for its ceramics workshops and pottery museum. This vibrant district offers a variety of entertainment options, including rock bars, nightclubs, and champuru stir-fry restaurants on lively side streets.
name: Kokusai dori

detail_description: Shuri Ryusen in Naha offers a unique dyeing experience using coral stones and dyes to create memorable cloth pieces. Located in Okinawa, an island surrounded by coral, visitors can partake in the traditional art of coral dye rubbing and cloth dyeing, resulting in one-of-a-kind creations. Coral is considered a symbol of happiness, making the dyed cloth a meaningful gift for loved ones.
name: 首里琉染

excerpt: Historic, atmospheric Shuri centers on medieval Shuri Castle, ringed by park-like grounds with a grove of sacred trees at Sonohyan-utaki. Visitors walk the centuries-old Kinjo Stone Road to enter Tamaudun Mausoleum, a grand tomb for rulers of the island’s former Ryukyu Kingdom. Small shrines, Okinawan restaurants, and old-fashioned teahouses fill the area, with casual student bars and cafes near college buildings.
detail_description: Shuri is a historic and atmospheric district known for its medieval Shuri Castle, surrounded by park-like grounds and sacred trees at Sonohyan-utaki. The area features the centuries-old Kinjo Stone Road leading to the Tamaudun Mausoleum, a grand tomb for former rulers of the Ryukyu Kingdom. Visitors can explore small shrines, Okinawan restaurants, and traditional teahouses while enjoying casual student bars and cafes near college buildings.
name: Shuri

detail_description: Shurijo Castle Park Public Parking Space P1 is conveniently located just a 5-minute walk from Tofu Shop Beans. This historical site was once the thriving center of politics, diplomacy, and culture in the Ryukyu Kingdom. Although some structures were lost in a fire in 2019, the park has been steadily expanding its visitor areas and making positive strides towards restoration.
name: Shurijo Castle Park Public Parking Space P1
address: レストセンター首里杜館, 1 Chome-1 Shurikinjocho, Naha, Okinawa 903-0815, Japan

excerpt: Lush public park with play equipment, a locomotive on display & an annual cherry blossom festival.
detail_description: Yogi Park in Naha, Japan is a stunning and peaceful public park that offers a lush natural setting. It features play equipment for children and even showcases a locomotive. The park is particularly famous for its annual cherry blossom festival, making it an ideal spot for cherry blossom hunting. With over 400 cherry trees, the park becomes a breathtaking sight when the blossoms appear from mid-February.
name: Yogi Park

detail_description: Kokusai-dori, also known as International Street, is the main thoroughfare in Naha, stretching about 2 kilometers through the city center. This bustling avenue is filled with a variety of shops, restaurants, and bars offering a lively atmosphere for visitors. It's a great place to browse through souvenir stores, island fashion boutiques, and Ryukyu glass shops showcasing jewelry inspired by the nearby ocean.
name: Kokusai-dori

excerpt: Museum shop offering traditional local crafts, including lacquerware, glassware, fabrics & ceramics.
detail_description: The Traditional Arts & Crafts Center is a museum shop located just a short walk from Shurijo Castle Park. It offers a wide range of traditional local crafts, such as lacquerware, glassware, fabrics, and ceramics. Additionally, visitors can explore SHURI RYUSEN, the first bingata dyeing research lab in Okinawa established in 1973.
name: Traditional Arts & Crafts Center
address: Tenbusu Naha, 伝統工芸館 2階, 3 Chome-2-10 Makishi, Naha, Okinawa 900-0013, Japan

detail_description: San-A Naha Main Place is a bustling shopping destination located in Naha, the vibrant capital city of Okinawa. As one of two major malls in the area, it provides a diverse selection of products, from large appliances to small accessories like hair clips. The mall features an expansive food court and various dining establishments, while also being conveniently surrounded by numerous eateries. Additionally, visitors can explore the adjacent hyakuen shop for enticing deals on a variety of items.
name: San-A Naha Main Place

excerpt: Hilly park with paved paths amid thick forest, a tranquil shrine & fireflies in early summer.
detail_description: Sueyoshi Park is a lovely and tranquil park with paved paths and thick forest. The park is popular among locals for peaceful walks, early summer fireflies, and wishing fortunes at the top of the shrine. It can be difficult to find, but there is ample parking.
name: Sueyoshi Park

detail_description: Naha Airport (OKA) serves as a gateway for both domestic and international flights, with regular arrivals from various Asian destinations. Located in Naha, it offers convenient access to the city center through the Okinawa Monorail, also known as Yui Rail. The airport is approximately 2 hours and 45 minutes away from Tokyo by flight.
name: Naha International Airport

excerpt: Oceanfront stretch with expansive views, patio dining & shops selling local fruits & sweets.
detail_description: Umikaji Terrace Senagajima is a popular spot for dining and shopping located on Senaga Island, just outside Naha in Tomigusuku. The shop-lined terraces offer stunning views of the nearby seaside, with over 40 shops selling gourmet dishes and various types of sweets made with unique Okinawan ingredients.
name: Umikaji Terrace Senagajima

excerpt: Polished exhibits about the city's cultural history, with displays of art & royal artifacts.
detail_description: The Naha City Museum of History offers a fascinating insight into the cultural heritage of Okinawa. Located in Palette Kumoji, this museum boasts a diverse collection donated by generous contributors. From royal documents to traditional arts and crafts, the exhibits showcase the rich history and unique identity of Okinawa. Visitors can escape the hustle and bustle of the city to explore this small yet impressive museum on the 4th floor of a shopping mall.
name: Naha City Museum of History

excerpt: Warm, easygoing option specializing in soba noodle soup paired with meat & a variety of toppings.
detail_description: "Okinawa Soba Eibun" is a laid-back eatery that specializes in serving Okinawan noodle soup made with wheat noodles. The dish features a light broth and is typically served with steamed fish cakes, pork belly, and various toppings. Unlike traditional soba noodles, the ones used here are made with 100% flour and do not contain buckwheat. This results in variations in color, thickness, and crimp of the noodles across different regions.
name: Eibun
address: ボーボー屋ビル, 1 Chome-5-14 Tsuboya, Naha, Okinawa 902-0065, Japan

detail_description: Tsuboya Pottery Street is a charming neighborhood in Naha, known for its artisan craft shops specializing in pottery. Taking a leisurely stroll through this area offers a peaceful and laid-back experience, providing a different perspective of Naha. Visitors can conclude their exploration with a visit to the Naha Municipal Tsuboya Pottery Museum to delve deeper into the art of pottery.
name: Tsuboya Pottery St

excerpt: Well-equipped park with an athletics stadium, outdoor swimming pool, sports fields & tennis courts.
detail_description: Onoyama Park, the largest park in Naha, is a fantastic destination just a few Yui Rail stops away from Kokusai Street. Families can enjoy its well-equipped facilities including an athletics stadium, outdoor swimming pool, sports fields, and tennis courts. The park also offers a serene atmosphere with Shinto shrines and a lovely pond. It's a popular spot for both locals and tourists to relax and engage in various activities.
name: Onoyama Park

excerpt: Lively, old-school covered shopping street with vendors of prepared food, produce & more.
detail_description: Sakaemachi Arcade is a vibrant and traditional covered street market that offers an array of local produce, prepared food and other goods. This bustling marketplace is a haven for foodies who love exploring different cuisines. While English menus may be scarce, the friendly vendors are more than willing to help visitors with their orders. The eateries in Sakaemachi Arcade mostly open at night, offering exciting culinary experiences that range from fresh sushi and ebi to charcoal-grilled beef tongue.
name: Sakaemachi Arcade

excerpt: Landmark retail road featuring a bustling covered shopping arcade with diverse merchandise.
detail_description: Heiwa Dori, a 336-meter-long covered shopping street near Kokusai-dori Street in Okinawa, is home to around 200 shops offering a diverse range of products. This bustling arcade features unique shops selling locally-made goods such as accessories, clothing, and snacks. Unlike its more touristy neighbor, Kokusai-dori Street, Heiwa Dori exudes a local and nostalgic vibe.
name: Heiwa Dori

detail_description: Naha City Tourist Information Center is a traveler-friendly spot offering a range of services such as money exchange, free Wi-Fi, and ticket assistance for transportation. The staff are known for being incredibly helpful and pleasant, providing valuable information on getting around Okinawa with the bus and recommending alternative services when needed. Visitors can also benefit from wheelchair and stroller rentals, as well as access to a nursing room.
name: Naha City Tourist Information Center
address: Tenbusu Naha, 伝統工芸館 1階, 3 Chome-2-10 Makishi, Naha, Okinawa 900-0013, Japan

detail_description: Tsuboya, specifically Tsuboya Yachimun Dori, is a charming limestone-paved street lined with studios showcasing the creations of renowned potters. Visitors can explore the Ceramics Museum and enjoy the ambiance of quaint cafes in this area. Following minimal damage during the war, reconstruction efforts began in the outskirts of the city, particularly around Tsuboya district near Kokusai Street.
name: Tsuboya

excerpt: Ryukyu Kingdom shrine founded in 1451 & rebuilt in 1975, set in parkland with Naha city views.
detail_description: Okino-gû Shrine, a historic site in Okinawa, was established in 1451 and reconstructed in 1975. It is located amidst scenic parkland offering panoramic views of Naha city. Unlike typical shrines in Japan, Okino-gû Shrine holds significance as the place where Amaterasu-Omikami descended before her journey to Ise. This shrine provides a unique perspective on traditional shrine architecture and grounds compared to those found elsewhere in the country.
name: Okino-gû Shrine

excerpt: Park with tree-lined paths, tennis courts & a lakefront jogging track, plus a butterfly garden.
detail_description: Manko Park (Kohagura Side) is a beautiful park in Naha, Okinawa that offers tree-lined paths, tennis courts, and a lakefront jogging track. It also features a butterfly garden for nature enthusiasts. Despite being located in the developed city of Naha, the park boasts a rich ecological system with mangroves, rare wild birds, and aquatic organisms. Visitors can enjoy leisurely walks through the park's picturesque surroundings.
name: Manko Park (Kohagura Side)

detail_description: Located just a short walk from Tamaudun, Shuri Kannon-do is one of the six temples near Shurijo Castle that has withstood the test of time over the past four centuries. Originally established in 1616 as part of Tenkai-ji temple, this site holds significance as a place for prayer and reflection. It is said to have witnessed miracles, instilling a sense of belief in Buddhism. Visitors often come here to seek blessings for safe travels to mainland Japan.
name: Shuri Kannondo

detail_description: Yui Rail Museum, located just a short walk from Yui Rails Naha Airport Station, is the southernmost rail museum in Japan. Although there are limited English notations, the museum offers a fascinating display of Japanese rail-related items and historical films. A unique feature is the opportunity to listen to traditional folk music broadcasted when the monorail arrives at each station.
name: Yui Rail Museum

detail_description: Manko Waterbird and Wetland Center offers a serene escape into nature, surrounded by lush greenery and wetlands. During winter, it becomes a sanctuary for migratory birds seeking shelter. Visitors can enjoy the peaceful boardwalk, observing various bird species, red crabs, and fish in their natural habitat. The center also features an outreach program focused on Japanese speakers. It's a perfect retreat from the bustling city life to immerse oneself in the tranquil beauty of wildlife.
name: Manko Waterbird and Wetland Center

detail_description: Asahibashi Station is known for its cleanliness and convenient location.
name: Asahibashi Station

excerpt: 300m-long, old cobblestone street sloping up toward Shuri Castle, with quiet residences & gardens.
detail_description: Kinjo Stone Road is a 300-meter-long cobblestone street that dates back to the 1500s in the Ryukyu Kingdom era. It slopes up toward Shuri Castle and is lined with quiet residences and gardens. Along the road, visitors can find Sui Dunchi restaurant, which offers local delicacies and features two gardens and a pond for a lovely dining experience.
name: Shuri Kinjo Town Stone-paved Road

detail_description: Shijo Hondori is a bustling shopping street that has become a must-visit for both bargain hunters and food lovers. Stretching from the Daiichi Makishi Public Market to Kokusai Street, this lively thoroughfare is lined with an eclectic mix of shops offering everything from clothing and antiques to unique souvenirs. What truly makes Shijo Hondori special is its impressive array of local culinary treats, including popular snack stalls and the famous brown sugar beans.
name: Shijo Hon-dori

excerpt: Traditional Chinese gate at Shurijo Castle; originally from the 16th century & later rebuilt.
detail_description: Shureimon Gate is a traditional Chinese gate located at Shurijo Castle, originally dating back to the 16th century and later rebuilt. Visitors can immerse themselves in the rich cultural experiences offered here, such as enjoying traditional music and savoring A5 Ishigaki beef from the Yaeyama Islands of Okinawa.
name: Shureimon Gate

detail_description: Tomari Port is a major ferry terminal in Okinawa, offering access to nearby islands. Unlike the tourist-filled Makishi market, this fish market is popular among locals. Visitors can purchase fresh seafood and snacks from the small convenience store located in the same building before embarking on their ferry journey. It's important to note that each ferry company has its own office and they are not interconnected, so travelers should be cautious. Additionally, those bringing vehicles must pay a fee near the ferry area.
name: Tomari Wharf ferry terminal building Tomarin Building.

detail_description: Heiwa Dori Shopping Street is a nostalgic area with a Showa-era ambiance, featuring various stores and souvenir shops. The street has a labyrinth-like layout with many rice cracker shops. Covered sheds provide shelter from the elements, leading to the Makishi Public Market. Exploring this arcade feels like an adventure, as it offers a mix of open and closed shops, creating an intriguing atmosphere reminiscent of a bygone era.
name: Heiwa Dori Shopping Street

detail_description: The Tsushima-maru Memorial Museum is a solemn tribute to the tragic sinking of the evacuation ship, Tsushima Maru, during World War II. The museum commemorates the 1,484 lives lost, including 767 children. Visitors can learn about this devastating event through exhibits featuring photographs and personal stories of the victims. While most displays are in Japanese with limited English explanations, free brochures in English are available for visitors.
name: Tsushima-maru Memorial Museum

excerpt: Culturally significant stone gate leading to a Ryukyu Kingdom castle & grove of sacred trees.
detail_description: Sonohyan-utaki Ishimon, also known as the Stone Gate of the Sonohyan Shrine, holds great cultural significance as it leads to a Ryukyu Kingdom castle and a sacred grove of trees. Situated on the grounds of Shuri Castle in Naha, Okinawa, this site is part of the UNESCO World Heritage Site called Gusuku Sites and Related Properties of the Kingdom of Ryukyu.
name: Sonohyan-utaki Ishimon (Stone gate of the Sonohyan Shrine)

excerpt: Museum focused on the history & production of Tsuboya pottery, with examples on display.
detail_description: Naha Municipal Tsuboya Pottery Museum is a showcase of the history and craftsmanship of Tsuboya pottery. It features over 300 pieces of traditional Okinawan pottery, offering insights into its production process, historical significance, and the working conditions of artisans. The museum also includes a reproduction of a traditional Okinawan house and an ancient kiln where pottery was made.
name: Naha Shiritsu Tsuboyayakimono Museum

detail_description: Gokoku Shrine is one of the three shrines located within Onoyama Park. It is a stunning place of worship dedicated to the victims of war. Visitors can purchase items to place for new year wishes at a nearby store and enjoy the serene surroundings with free parking, vending machines, and bathrooms available on the park grounds. The shrine features a captivating statue of a girl with a seagull in her hair, sparking curiosity about its story.
name: Okinawa Gokoku Shrine

detail_description: Nestled quietly on the northern edge of Shuri Castle Park, Enkaku-ji Temple offers a serene escape from the bustling crowds. Founded in 1492 by King Sho Shin as a family temple for the second Sho lineage, this historic site became the head temple of the Rinzai sect of Zen Buddhism in the Ryukyu Kingdom.
name: Enkaku-ji
